\f2\b \cf2 The Democracy Clock
\f1\b0  is a standing, longitudinal report that measures and documents changes in the condition of democratic governance in the United States over time. It tracks both erosion and repair of democratic norms, institutions, and practices using a consistent, evidence-based framework. The report is updated on a fixed cadence and preserved in archival editions to create a durable public record.\
\
The purpose of the Democracy Clock is not to persuade, predict, or advocate. It exists to 
\f2\b make democratic change legible
\f1\b0 , particularly when that change is incremental, normalized, or obscured by political noise. Democracies rarely collapse suddenly. They weaken\'97or recover\'97through cumulative decisions, precedents, and institutional shifts. The Democracy Clock records that accumulation.\
\
The report is designed for use by journalists and producers seeking factual grounding; policy staff and institutional leaders monitoring governance risk; educators and researchers studying democratic systems; and citizens seeking explanation rather than commentary. It is a public reference, not an opinion column, electoral forecast, or partisan document.\
